2) What is the role of JVM in Java execution?
-->The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) acts as a runtime engine that loads, verifies, and executes Java bytecode,
    enabling the "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA) capability.

3) Explain the lifecycle of a Java program in terms of JVM.
-->The lifecycle of a Java program within the JVM involves several distinct stages: Loading, Linking (Verification, Preparation, Resolution),
    Initialization, Execution, and (eventually) Unloading.

4) What are the main components of JVM?
-->The main components of the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) include the ClassLoader Subsystem (loads, links, and initializes code),
    Runtime Data Areas (manages memory like Heap and Stacks), 
    and
    the Execution Engine (interprets/compiles bytecode).

5) What is the role of the Class Loader in JVM?
-->The Class Loader is a critical subsystem of the JVM that dynamically loads Java class files (.class) into memory only when they are 
    required at runtime, rather than all at once.
    It is responsible for locating, loading, linking, and initializing classes, ensuring they are available for the Java application to 
    create objects or use static methods

6) What is the role of the Execution Engine?
-->responsible for running the Java bytecode that has been loaded into the memory.

7) How does the JVM perform memory management?
-->The JVM manages memory automatically by allocating space for objects on the Heap and storing method calls/local variables on the Stack. 

8) What are the different memory areas in JVM?
-->The JVM defines several runtime data areas for program execution, primarily divided into shared areas (Heap, Method Area)
    and thread-isolated areas (Stack, PC Register, Native Stack).

9) What is method area and heap area?
-->Method Area (Class Area)
      Purpose: Stores class structure, metadata, bytecode of methods, static variables, and the runtime constant pool.
      Lifecycle: Created when the JVM starts and is shared among all threads.
      Implementation: Often called Metaspace in modern JVMs (Java 8+), which resides in native memory, not the Java heap.
      Key Characteristic: Holds information necessary to define the class structure. 
